Outraged. Provincal MEC for health, Dr Phophi Ramathuba visited the Elim Hospital last Friday in search of answers following the death of a 83-year-old patient at the hospital.Date: 06 February 2017 By: Kaizer NengovhelaViewed: 5754A unit manager and a junior nurse at the Elim Hospital have been suspended following the horrific death of an 83-year-old gogo.Initial reports state that Mrs Mujaji Manganyi of the Xikuhele Village near Waterval sustained third degree burn wounds and passed away after falling in a bath filled with hot water at the hospital last Thursday (2 February). Her family now wants to see justice done, and claims her death was a result of gross negligence on the side of hospital staff.After learning about the incident, the provincial Department of Health (DoH) suspended a unit manager and a junior nurse at the hospital. &ldquo;The department has appointed a high-level team to investigate the circumstances surrounding this case of alleged gross negligence,&rdquo; said the DoH&rsquo;s MEC Dr Phophi Ramathuba.&ldquo;The two staff members have since been suspended as the persons responsible for the care and safety of all patients in the unit,&rdquo; said Ramathuba. She further added that all others involved in the alleged negligent act will be held accountable.Read the full report in this week&rsquo;s edition of the Limpopo Mirror.Kaizer Nengovhela started writing stories for Limpopo Mirror more than a decade ago, in 2 000. Prior to that he had a five year stint at Phala-Phala FM as sports presenter. In 2005 Kaizer received an award from the province&#39;s premier as Best Sports Presenter. The same year he was also nominated as Best Sports Reporter by the Makhado Municipality. Kaizer was awarded the Mathatha Tsedu award in 2014.Email: kaizerdo@webmail.co.zaMore photos... 